leads.headline: No significant vulnerabilities identified
leads.analysis:
Based on analysis of the provided code files, no significant security vulnerabilities were identified. The code appears to consist of static HTML files and a basic JavaScript manifest file for a web application.

The HTML files (404.html, 422.html, 500.html) contain standard markup for displaying error pages. They do not contain any user-controllable input or server-side logic that could introduce vulnerabilities.

The JavaScript manifest file (application.js) specifies dependencies using relative paths and standard directives. It does not contain any custom code that could introduce vulnerabilities.

Overall, the limited functionality and lack of server-side processing or user input suggests these files do not contain exploitable security flaws based on the provided code alone. However, a full assessment would require analyzing the entire application codebase and infrastructure.
